&lt;https://emsenn.net/library/domains/humanities/domains/sociology/domains/work/domains/governance/terms/precedent/>
  rdf:type schema:Article ;
  schema:url &lt;https://emsenn.net/library/domains/humanities/domains/sociology/domains/work/domains/governance/terms/precedent/> ;
  schema:name "Precedent" ;
  schema:description "A Precedent is a triple (p, t₀, J) — a doubly-settled proposition p ∈ H*_{t₀}, the history t₀ at which the decision was made, and a propagation condition derived from the Grothendieck topology J that determines whether p persists to future histories. The defining structure: p is a precedent iff p ∈ Fix(RelationalHistoryFiberTransferringNucleus(t₀)) — iff p is forward-stable at t₀, meaning it exists in the image of every independent one-step extension restriction map. Precedent-following at history t \u003e t₀ = a lifting: there exists a doubly-settled p_t ∈ H*_t with H(t → t₀)(p_t) = p, ensuring the precedent is carried by the history without loss. Precedent-overruling = a change to J such that p ∈ Fix(Δ_{t₀}) fails in the new topology, geometrically: a covering morphism f: R' → R between toposes that does not preserve the fixed sublocale containing p. Distinguished from Breach (failure to discharge a duty), Defection (incompatible output), and Delegation (which transfers authority but not accountability): precedent neither delegates nor discharges — it transmits normative structure forward through the presheaf." ;
  schema:datePublished "2026-03-21" ;
  schema:dateModified "2026-03-21" ;
  schema:about &lt;https://emsenn.net/library/domains/humanities/domains/sociology/domains/work/domains/governance/terms/precedent/> ;
  rdfs:seeAlso "Judgment, Institution, NormativeSystem, Foundation, Act, Gap, History, Accountability" ;
  schema:identifier &lt;https://emsenn.net/library/domains/humanities/domains/sociology/domains/work/domains/governance/terms/precedent/> .

